@realmoney Sep 24, 2019 | 04:55 PM EDT DOUG KASS Why the Impeachment Hearings May Be Negative for the Markets * Politics and markets are now intertwined and enmeshed * The President is "Making Economic Uncertainty and Market Volatility Great Again"

I have been of the view for some time that the president's behavior would begin to adversely impact our markets -- specifically that Trump is Making Economic Uncertainty and Market Volatility Great Again (#MUVGA) Many have normalized the behavior of the current Administration

but the (possible) impeachment hearings could provide another headwind to global economic growth (at a time that growth rate is quite vulnerable and the business cycle is mature) and to our stock market by delaying any "progress" between China and the U.S. in their trade

negotiations. Specifically, it seems to me that China will now not be in any rush to proceed swiftly in coming to a trade resolution -- likely preferring to await the outcome of the hearings. After all, why would China agree to a trade agreement when President Trump's

very political existence is in question? Impeachment hearings could take quite a while, perhaps even going into the middle of next year. And if the hearings take six months (or more), and are then closing in on the November 2020 election, wouldn't China then just wait out

the results of the presidential contest? As a result, with no clear outcome likely forthcoming to the trade issue, consumer and business confidence may recede. Importantly, corporations will almost certainly continue to defer business fixed investment and wait out the outcome of

the delayed trade negotiations. As discussed yesterday, my corporate profit and economic growth expectations are well below consensus. Given today's news I might be too optimistic. @jimcramer @Sarge986 @tomkeene @SquawkCNBC @cnbcfastmoney @michaelsantoli @carlquintanilla

@realmoney Sep 24, 2019 | 03:49 PM EDT DOUG KASS The Anti Confident * There is no secret sauce * The investment mosaic remains more complicated than any time in history * Hide your children and portfolios from anyone that expresses overly confident views on the markets

No doubt the same practitioners who were confidently buoyed by the reversal of the -25 handle decline in the S&P last Wednesday (to breakeven) will now have second thoughts about the near-term direction of stocks. No doubt they will fail to state that their previous forecasts

were wrong and ill advised. And perhaps, with possible impeachment hearings about to commence, as well as the rest of the policy circus occurring in Washington D.C., investors will finally recognize the folly and reassess of the valuation rise in stocks this year (which

contributed to the entirety of the gains year to date). I certainly don't possess the answers to the complicated investment mosaic (there is no special sauce!) but, through a calculator, logic of argument and hard-hitting analysis I have concluded that downside risk dwarfs

upside reward. Again for emphasis: never in my investing career have there so many potential social, economic, political, geopolitical and market outcomes (many of them adverse). The aforementioned and oft used phrase in my Diary really sums it up.
I am aggressively short positioned. @tomkeene
